## Conjecture (CPRR)
- Hypothesis: rotating across the 4 real workspace subdirs is
  enough coverage for the scope honesty contract — each one is
  a representative \"real subdirectory\" with its own tree shape.
  Random path generation would produce nonexistent dirs that
  grep can't walk, defeating the test.
- Hypothesis: path-traversal fuzzing at varying depths (1-5
  levels of ..) catches a class of safe-path? regressions that
  fixed-depth tests miss.

## Validation
- Property 1 ran 100 trials × 4 scopes uniformly distributed
  via rng-element. All pass.
- Property 3 ran 100 trials with depth in [1,5]. All rejected
  with \"Unsafe\" prefix.
- Filter logic strips \"Binary file ...\" headers and grep:
  prefixed errors so only real match lines are checked. Without
  the filter, binary file warnings would false-positive.

## Refutation / known limits
- The property uses string-prefix? rather than exact path match.
  If a file outside src/sage happened to be named with that
  prefix (e.g., src/sage-extra/foo.scm) it would slip through.
  Acceptable for this codebase.
- Property 1 grep'd for the literal pattern \"define\" because
  it's universally common. A rarer pattern would give better
  coverage of the head -200 truncation behaviour but make the
  property more brittle.
- No property yet for the file_pattern arg (basename glob
  semantics). Could be added in a follow-up.
- The 4-scope rotation is hard-coded to this repo's dir layout.
  If src/sage gets renamed, the property breaks. Acceptable
  in exchange for using real grep-walkable paths.

